Spawning a shell subprocess to check for executable existence on the PATH is inefficient and less portable. Per the general rules, `Bun.which()` should be used for this purpose. You can temporarily modify `process.env.PATH` to search a specific set of directories using `Bun.which()` without the overhead of a subprocess.

```typescript
async function bunResolvableFromHookPath(): Promise<boolean> {
  const hookPath = "/usr/bin:/bin:/usr/local/bin:" + (process.env.HOME ?? "") + "/.bun/bin";
  const oldPath = process.env.PATH;
  try {
    process.env.PATH = hookPath;
    return Bun.which("bun") !== null;
  } finally {
    process.env.PATH = oldPath;
  }
}
```

